# Command lnav

## What does this command do:

A log file viewer for the terminal

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install lnav`
For Raspberry Pi install using: `sudo apt install lnav`
For Mac install using: `homebrew install lnav`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `lnav`
For Raspberry Pi run: `lnav`
For Mac run: `lnav`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://docs.lnav.org/en/v0.13.1/

## Command options

# View a log file:
lnav /var/log/syslog

# Load all files in a directory:
lnav /var/log

# Recursively load files from directory hierarchies:
lnav -r /var/log

# Load older rotated log files as well:
lnav -R /var/log

# Watch the output of a shell command:
lnav -e 'make -j4'

# Run in headless (no curses UI) mode:
lnav -n /var/log/syslog

# Do not open default syslog if no files given:
lnav -N

# Treat stdin as a log file:
lnav -t

# Execute a command after files are loaded (prefix: : ; | /):
lnav -c ':filter-in error' /var/log/syslog

# Execute commands from a file:
lnav -f /path/to/commands.lnav

# Execute a shell command and display output:
lnav -e 'journalctl -f'

# Add an additional configuration directory:
lnav -I /path/to/config/dir

# Print warnings about lnav's configuration:
lnav -W

# Check files against configuration and report errors:
lnav -C /var/log/syslog

# Display internal help text on startup:
lnav -H

# Print version information:
lnav -V

# Do not print informational messages (quiet mode):
lnav -q

# Install format files:
lnav -i /path/to/format.json

# Switch to management mode:
lnav -m config get

# Update formats installed from git repositories:
lnav -u

# Key bindings (while in lnav):
# ?    View/leave online help
# q    Quit the program
